; string-byte-fold-src-shim.fk — string_byte_fold for the fkwu --src surface:
; the one missing name, implemented as real Form tissue.
;
; preludes: form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/str-byte-at.fk
;
; Probed 2026-07-17 on this surface: `string_byte_fold` (fold a step closure
; over the raw UTF-8 bytes of a string, including NUL) is a sibling-kernel
; native (form-kernel-go/main.go registerNative) with no fkwu counterpart, so
; a cell whose prelude chain touches it (sha256.fk's streaming entry, first
; met by the source-artifact seal band) compiles RED under --src even when
; that lane is exercised only through the native on the siblings.
;
; Unlike record-src-shim's honestly-empty door, this shim is the REAL
; contract in Form: (string_byte_fold s acc step) folds step(acc, byte) left
; to right over every byte of s, byte values 0..255 via str-byte-at (the
; four-way-proven raw-byte read). No degradation on the value path — the
; same bytes reach the same step in the same order as the Go native.
;
; The honest wall: the loop recurses once per byte. It is written in tail
; position; a walker without tail-call reuse spends a stack frame per byte,
; so multi-hundred-KB messages may hit the stack wall where the Go native's
; loop would not. Named, not hidden — the shim's band witnesses the fold on
; real digests; the wall moves when the walk door learns tail reuse.
;
; Proven by: form-stdlib/tests/string-byte-fold-src-shim-band.fk (--src
; surface only — on the sibling kernels the native carries this name).

(do
    (defn sbf-fold-loop (s i n acc step)
        (if (lt i n)
            (sbf-fold-loop s (add i 1) n (step acc (str-byte-at s i)) step)
            acc))
    (defn string_byte_fold (s acc step)
        (sbf-fold-loop s 0 (str_len s) acc step))
    0)
